  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Letter to Misu on the Writings of Su Dongpo
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    As I observe the present age, the prose of Su Dongpo has flourished greatly in our time, and what scholar does not carry his words in heart and hum them aloud? Yet if one merely savors his writing without grasping its essence, even should one imitate and borrow from him, would this not fall far short of truly capturing his spirit and bone?

    Therefore, a scholar ought simply to follow his own measure and advance toward what brings him ease—there is no need to force oneself into artificial mimicry and lose one's natural quality. This too is a principle of importance.

    Yet you and I, though we have not long studied his texts, often find our sentence patterns already bearing a subtle resemblance to his. Is this not because something within us resonates silently with him? Of late I have composed several pieces that bear something of his manner. I send them to you now, hoping you will examine them and grace me with your instruction. Forgive the want of ceremony in this letter.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Su Dongpo (蘇東坡, 1037-1101), also known as Su Shi, was a celebrated Song Dynasty poet, essayist, and calligrapher whose literary style profoundly influenced later generations of East Asian writers.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'spirit and bone' (風骨) refers to the innermost essence and vigor of a literary work—the qualities that give it life and character beyond mere surface imitation.
  - key: ''
    value: This appears to be a personal letter to a fellow scholar, likely a peer or mentor, discussing the challenge of learning from a great master without losing one's own authentic voice.
